title: Happy Birthday Jason
report:
Welcome back to the Jart Report after a week four that brought blowouts across the board this week. Despite the snoozers, we still learned a lot about all of our teams this week and we are excited to bring you the analysis heading into an exciting week five.

Week Four Recap

To start, we are going to be looking back at how week four unfolded versus the predictions that the Jart Team put together. The team strives to learn from previous weeks to make the most informed predictions, and as we move into the middle of the season we hope to improve in accuracy considerably. We will go matchup by matchup and look at what we learned as the season begins to take shape.

Team Horses vs I Got a Half Chubb:

Prediction: Team Horses by 11.6

Reality: I Got a Half Chubb by 52.3

What we said: Two teams currently trending in different directions after Week Three, CJ will be looking to get back on track while Folbe looks to keep up the high scoring momentum. Josh Allen is faced with a highly enticing matchup against the Texans, while DK draws a SF defense that was just torched by Davante Adams. For CJ, Chubb and Dmont draw favorable games against Minnesota and Detroit respectively. While the RB production should be good, we are weary about the potential tough matchups at QB and TE, while we are in a wait and see approach on how Diontae Johnson returns from injury. While we could see this game going either way, continued high level performance from some key players propel Folbe, as we have Team Horses by 11.6.

What we saw: The Jart Report wanted to believe that Folbe scoring 137 wasn’t just a once-in-a-season fluke that cost Jart Nation a loss, but instead we see that that is truly all it was. Allen and DK performed well, and a second great week from Zeke was certainly encouraging. But the rest of the team was absolute and utter garbage. No one else scored more than 5.4 ($21 man Tim Patrick), and it looks like Logan Thomas is going to miss at least one week. At least Tee Higgins is back soon? For CJ, a good bounce back week was severely dampened by a knee injury that will sideline RIP Dmont for at least 4 weeks. Diontae Johnson returning was a big boost for the squad, and Buffalo feasted on turnover prone Davis Mills. Never was in doubt.

Team Ross vs Real Brothers:

Prediction: Real Brothers by 12.9

Reality: Real Brothers by 26.04

What we said: In one of the more unique matchups, we come into this one with the 1-2 team averaging almost 13 PPG more than the 3-0 team. For Aross, Dalvin Cook is expected to be back, which honestly does not make much of a difference and Alexander Mattison has proven he can put up the same numbers in replacement. After struggling with Detroit some last week, Lamar draws a tough matchup in Denver’s D. Mike Davis and Myles Gaskin will both look to get going this week, with Davis drawing the more favorable matchup. Antonio Brown has been rumored to be receiving the start this week, so we will certainly be keeping an eye on that story as it develops. For Jart, Jalen Hurts and Miles Sanders draw Kansas City in what looks to be a big bounceback week after struggling against the Cowboys. Ja’Marr Chase draws the always awful Jaguars to kick off the week on TNF, while Brandin Cooks will likely be receiving throws early and often with the Texans as massive underdogs. The thing to watch most here is D’Andre Swift’s usage is what will likely be a low scoring and close game throughout, as well as if Tyreek Hill can get back to producing. We expect both of these things to happen, and we like Real Brothers by 12.9 this week.

What we saw: Dalvin Cook was in and out of the game, hindering his output and setting the tone for what was a disappointing day for Aross. Mike Davis somehow found the end zone despite having 13 carries for 14 yards, which was of great frustration to your team at the Jart Report. Myles Gaskin was the epitome of the trash can emoji, while Keenan Allen struggled to get going and AB was just missed a couple times for a TD. Lamar looked fine but not amazing, and it is not usually a good sign when 2 of your 3 double digit scorers are your TE and your Kicker. Back to the drawing board for a team that is lucky to be 3-1, but is still in the thick of it. For Jart, it was the return of Tyreek Hill that led this team, although Jalen Hurts continues to provide high level play. The terrible management you have come to expect was on display for Jart, as Saquon Barkley and Cordarelle Patterson combined for 59.2 on his bench. This team has the firepower to hang with anyone in the league, but needs to get it onto the field at the same time.

Nooni vs Team ACL Tears:

Prediction: Nooni by 17.1

Reality: Team ACL Tear by 70.82

What we said: This is our prediction for blowout of the week. We do like what Nooni is working towards here and the team receives a big boost from McCaffrey’s injury, and we expect bounceback days from Allen Robinson and Tyler LockettE. For JL, Kyler Murray looks to find the endzone through the air this week after failing to do so last week, while Diggs and Deebo both draw favorable matchups. I bet you thought I was gonna say this was gonna be a blowout win for Lopey. But in what will probably ruin the integrity of the Jart Report and make us look like idiots come next week, we are calling a breakout week from Nooni and some struggles from JL. In a pick we want to hide from, we like Nooni by 17.1.

What we saw: Lol. That’s all. We at the Jart Report apologize for picking Nooni.

United Nations vs GRIDDY GANG:

Prediction: GRIDDY GANG by 13.3

Reality: GRIDDY GANG by 32.08

What we said: These are two very different 2-1 teams. As in one deserves to be 2-1 and the other doesn’t. In the absence of Christian McCaffrey, there is simply too much firepower on GRIDDY GANG to be overcome. A massive day from Derrick Henry is certainly expected against the Jets, while the Griddy receiving duo should all provide solid days to complement. DJ Moore and James Robinson will be the guys to watch on MW’s team, to see if they can continue to build off of last week’s success. We like GRIDDY GANG by 13.3.

What we saw: Derrick popped, and the elite WR duo of the GRIDDY GANG JJeffs and Scary Terry showed out. Darrell Henderson looked good in his return from injury, and overall this team continues to prove they are a Top 3 team week in and out. The TD luck was there for MW, but the lack of yardage in the absence of Christian McCaffrey was too much to overcome. Suddenly this team has serious WR2 and FLEX questions, as well as potentially RB2 while McCaffrey remains out. Unless something changes quick, the next couple of weeks do not look promising for MW.

Mike Williams WR1 vs Team Dmichs:

Prediction: Dmichs by 7.2

Reality: Dmichs 18.3

What we said: A matchup that would have been decided by over 70 points last week, these teams come in with very different levels of momentum. All signs point to Brad winning easily, but we at the Jart Report do not see this one going down that way. We expect Dak and Amari to reestablish their Week One connection against a solid but not unbeatable Carolina defense, while Jonathan Taylor has the potential for a big day against a Miami defense that was just torched by Payton Barber, while Devin Singletary and Odell Beckham Jr. both have very favorable matchups. Travis Kelce should cancel out much of Mahomes, and the Jart Report is skeptical on Elijah Mitchell and Kareem Hunt. In what we expect to be a fairly high scoring matchup, we like Dmichs by 7.2.

What we saw: Dak Prescott and Amari Cooper did hook up for a TD this week, and Jonathan Taylor did finally find the endzone against the weak Dolphins run D. OBJ and Kelce both had disappointing days (OBJ’s being the bigger cause for concern), but solid performances from Hollywood Brown, Baltimore’s D/ST, and Matt Prater put Dmichs over the top. For Brad, great games for Mahomes, Gibson, Hunt, and Boyd were offset by disappointing performances from Adams, Kittle, WR1.6, Tennessee D/ST, and Greg Joseph. While the Jart Report expects BMW to get more than 1 catch a game, his days as WR2 are likely in the past. The Jart Report doesn’t feel great about either of these teams moving forward, but a nice win for Dmichs.

NN vs Tompa Bay:

Prediction: Tompa Bay by 9.8

Reality: Tompa Bay by 26.74

What we said: While we will keep a watchful eye on what NN does in the QB department this week (Jart Report’s best guess is Baker Mayfield), the Jart Report sees a lot more to like on the Tompa Bay side. While both teams are in need of a win after rough starts to the season (outside of Week 2 for Bank), we expect some regression from Cooper Kupp this week as teams begin to really key in on making someone else (Robert Woods) beat them through the air. Joe Mixon should have a good night on TNF against the lowly Jaguars, but expectations are somewhat tampered for Marvin Jones Jr and Courtland Sutton this week. Tom Brady should have a monster game against his old team, while Chase Edmonds, Calvin Ridley, and Julio Jones all draw favorable matchups. This likely won’t be the highest scoring matchup of the week, but we like Tompa Bay by 9.8.

What we saw: We at the Jart Report are stumped. We can’t seem to find the words to describe just how bad NN’s team is. With Cooper Kupp returning to Earth, he and Najee Harris are really the only hope for a team that has now entered into the annual Joe Mixon week-to-week injury season. QB play remains poor, while WR2 and FLEX provide inconsistent production, and the TE position remains TD dependent. There is not much to like here, and not much to trade to try to build. While we hope NN improves, we have a tough time seeing it without a favorable trade.

Ratios were pretty even this week throughout the league, with the majority of ratios falling in the 100s. Ratios were much lower this week, with 197 coming in as the 3rd highest this week after 197.5 was the 8th highest last week. MW was a surprise coming in with the lowest ratio, given that he did not score that many points and took the loss. Not a great sign for the team.

A lot of shakeups this week, with Dmichs returning near the top in points possible, and Folbe falling back down to the bottom. No one played their best possible lineup this week, with CJ coming the closest. Jart was by far the worst lineup picker this week, with Saquon Barkley and Cordarelle Patterson going off while Miles Sanders and D’Andre Swift struggled.

Transaction Analysis

In this segment we will look at the transactions from this week and rate the best and worst one in the opinion of the Jart Report.

Best Transaction: JL, Dawson Knox, $1. Idek how this is happening. But every TE that Jonah touches turns to gold.

Honorable Mention: CJ, Latavius Murray, $1. While it remains to be seen how this RB rotation will all shake out with Ty’Son healthy, if Latavius takes control of the work $1 is a steal for a solid FLEX play.

Worst Transaction: NN, Kirk Cousins, $1. While NN didn’t pay much to acquire him, he once again dropped a QB who outscored the one he picked up. This week was quite the sizeable difference between Daniel Jones and Kirk Cousins, as Cousins finished as the worst starter at the QB position for the league this week.

Hororable Mention: Folbe, Tim Patrick, $21. Could turn out to be fine, but right now looks like a major overpay for a WR whose ceiling is certainly limited, and floor may be quite low, especially with Bridgewater sidelined now.

On To Week Five!

It is now time to preview this week’s matchups!

Team Ross vs Mike Williams WR1: Two teams coming off disappointing losses last week, on paper this looks to be one of the more even matchups of the week. Lamar Jackson and Patrick Mahomes both provide the potential for electric QB play, although Mahomes has been more consistent so far this year. Dalvin Cook has a fabulous matchup with the Lions, and look for Aross to pursue Damien Williams heavily to slide into the RB2 role. If AJB can go that will provide a nice boost to the FLEX position that struggled greatly a week ago, and Keenan Allen and AB should both see improved weeks. For Brad, Gibson and Hunt both remain difficult for the Jart Report to fully trust despite solid seasons so far, while Tyler Boyd is downgraded if Tee Higgins suits up. Bounceback weeks for Davante Adams and Mike Williams are to be expected, but will it be enough? We think not at the Jart Report, as we have Team Ross by 15.4.

Tompa Bay vs Dmichs: Another intriguing matchup, both of these teams have shown a lot of volatility so far this season. We expect one of these teams to show up this week while the other does not, but we could see it going either way. Ultimately, after having one of his worst weeks in recent memory, the Jart Report expects Travis Kelce to get back on track in a major way, and for the Dak-Amari connection to continue to kindle its flame. For Bank, Robert Woods has the chance to have a massive day against the suspect Seahawk defense if Kupp doesn’t steal the show, and Ridley could feast on the Jets D unless the game script goes run heavy early. This one has the potential for a lot of points, and while we like it in a blowout, since we can’t choose which direction we’ll take Dmichs by 5.4.

GRIDDY GANG vs Team Horses: Unless Week 3 Folbe shows up, this one will be over quickly. Examining matchups across the board, we like Josh Allen to have a massive day against KC as Jalen Hurts just did and outscore Russell Wilson. Zeke should continue success and Chris Carson bounces back, but very good matchups for Elder Horse and Darrell provide a massive advantage to GRIDDY GANG. Getting Tee Higgins back will be big for Horses, but DK likely can’t offset the trio of Jefferson, Godwin, and McLaurin. Replacing Logan Thomas will be interesting to watch, but there is simply too much going GRIDDY GANG’s way. Some off-brand performances from Jason coupled by explosion from Folbe is needed to pull the upset here, and we don’t see that happening. We like GRIDDY GANG by 22.7.

Team ACL Tear vs NN: Oof. The consensus best and worst teams so far this season face off, and there just is not much to say here. The Jart Report likes Cousins and Najee to both have big days, and for Cooper Kupp to either have a massive showing against Seattle on TNF or be completely locked down. RB2 remains a concern for this team, along with TE and FLEX. For JL, the sustainability of Deebo Samuel’s play is a major question mark along with CEH, but there is a lot to like for this team. CeeDee Lamb should bounce back nicely against the Giants, while Kyler Murray has historically performed well against the 49ers, albeit injuries do not plague that defense in the same way this season. NN is going to need some massive performances to pull off the upset, and while we can see its plausibility, we like Team ACL Tear by 32.6.

Nooni vs United Nations: Neither of these teams are good. So the Jart Report team is unsure of what to expect. Ultimately, the play of Stafford and Kamara coupled with what should be a better performance from Chuba Hubbard give Nooni the spark needed to beat the McCaffrey-less Merrill. This is likely the week DJ Moore comes back down to Earth some while being covered by Slay, and we like Tyler Lockett to turn in a solid outing. James Robinson will likely be the wildcard here, but we don’t expect him to maintain the same elite production he has turned in the last two weeks. Nooni by 12.6.

Real Brothers vs I Got a Half Chubb: The Jart Report’s game of the week, two Top 4 teams in the league so far face off, both coming off wins. There is a lot to like about both of these teams, with the biggest question mark on either starting lineup being how Latavius Murray fills in for the injured David Montgomery. The Jart Report hates missing a chance to face off against a son, but nonetheless we expect a lot of points to be put up in this one. Thielen should find the endzone at least once against Detroit, but Hopkins and Diontae draw tough matchups in San Fran and Denver respectively. The play of Cordarelle Patterson is a surprising new x-factor for The Family, as on paper a matchup against the Jets suggests a big day. We fully expect Jart to make some lineup errors this week, and which Tyreek Hill shows up will certainly be a major factor. A matchup we would like to be pretty much even if there were no injuries, the inability of RIP Dmont to suit up gives the slight edge to Jart. We like Real Brothers by 2.2.

Best Player at Each Position

In this segment we will predict who will have the best fantasy performance this week at each position, along with who they are rostered by (if they are currently rostered).

QB: Josh Allen

RB: Derrick Henry

WR: Robert Woods

TE: Travis Kelce

D/ST: Buccaneers D/ST

K: Matt Gay

New Segment: IBM Jartson Trade Assistant

In this segment we create one trade of perceived equal value by the Jart Report’s view that we think should happen. Trades involving Jart will be excluded from consideration.

Aross: Antonio Brown

MW: Javonte Williams

MW gets reunited with Antonio Brown and helps solve some WR issues, while Aross adds a solid RB to replace Mike Davis. While it would leave MW with some RB questions before McCaffrey comes back, it was the most need-filling trade the team could find that didn’t involve Dmichs giving Jart Kelce :)

New Segment: Juju Award

Submitted by long time reader, first time commenter JL, this award goes to the team who seems to be bonding the best (we prefer to call this The Family award). As soon as Bob Onions hits the griddy after scoring a TD this one will be decided for the team, but until then we give the award to NN. Nothing bonds a team together like adversity, and no one is facing more currently. While it seems a little early to be tanking for Bryce Young, we respect the commitment.
